('105', '113', 'Marcelle Heath', 'marcelleheath@yahoo.com', 'http://www.offislandnovel.wordpress.com', '70.59.151.64', '2009-07-01 13:52:43', '2009-07-01 17:52:43', 'You\'re welcome Roxane! I LOVE your story Queries involving Tyler Perry. Favorite new word: unbeaweavable. Favorite answer: Grease my face with Vaseline, remove my earrings, and snatch their weaves, while singing a Jill Scott song.\r\nHilarious!', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; PPC Mac OS X Mach-O; en-US; rv:1.8.1.20) Gecko/20081217 Firefox/2.0.0.20', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('106', '113', 'Roxane', 'roxane@roxanegay.com', 'http://www.roxanegay.com', '71.13.217.52', '2009-07-01 18:15:12', '2009-07-01 22:15:12', 'I\'m glad you enjoyed that story. I had fun with it. I love obsessing over the plague that is Tyler Perry.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; Intel Mac OS X 10.5; en-US; rv:1.9.0.11) Gecko/2009060214 Firefox/3.0.11', '', '105', '1', 'N'),
('107', '117', 'Ethel Rohan', 'ethelrohan@gmail.com', '', '24.4.57.196', '2009-07-02 11:39:03', '2009-07-02 15:39:03', 'Congratulations on Pindeldyboz and on this latest pub. \"Perfect Like Normal We Practice\" is another fine story, well done. I love the title, you do titles so well, and the narrator\'s straight-forward style works really well for such a painful piece. How we suffer ... It is a sad story, but I also felt hopeful that our narrator would grow up to be a different, more empowered, kind of woman ... Thanks for the read.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-US; rv:1.9.0.11) Gecko/2009060215 Firefox/3.0.11', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('108', '117', 'margosita', 'margaret.lafleur@gmail.com', '', '71.202.220.236', '2009-07-02 14:46:01', '2009-07-02 18:46:01', 'I adored the title, as well.  Though the title of this post is a bit misleading- two nice things to report!  It\'s a bit more than \"not much\"!', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; Intel Mac OS X 10.4; en-US; rv:1.9.0.11) Gecko/2009060214 Firefox/3.0.11', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('110', '117', 'Angi', 'angi.becker.stevens@gmail.com', 'http://angibeckerstevens.blogspot.com', '69.14.150.65', '2009-07-03 22:02:54', '2009-07-04 02:02:54', 'Love that story!\r\nDoesn\'t it seem like hearing back from publications really waxes and wanes? I feel like even though I submit very regularly, there will be periods of time where my inbox is like a ghost town, and then I will hear from multiple places at once even if I submitted at all different times.\r\nI am in the limbo of multiple rewrite requests. Which are far lovelier than rejections, just tough on the nerves sometimes.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; Intel Mac OS X 10.5; en-US; rv:1.9.0.10) Gecko/2009042315 Firefox/3.0.10', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('111', '113', 'Michael James', 'iamnotspikelee@gmail.com', 'http://www.michaeljamesmartin.wordpress.com', '70.218.25.57', '2009-07-04 19:56:35', '2009-07-04 23:56:35', 'My family comes from the South. Grew up a little bit there, in California (Northern and Southern). Grew up in the city. From surburbia to LA County, where cops get shot in the head a block up the street, in front of the elementary school. We have some of the stereotypical African-American family quirks, although, we also have the un-stereotypical family quirks. Which proves to me those stereotypes people seem to latch onto are kind of silly, and usually derive from environment and also the fact the African-American experience in this country simply causes certain characteristics embed onto the people. If you are not Caucasian, you understand.\r\n\r\nI don\'t write about ethnicity often, or perhaps, exclusively. I like to tell stories, and stories are not ethnically bound. People, when you strip away such things, are not the same, but hold many universal aspects.\r\n\r\nNow, there are many things at work -- I feel I must write about ethnicity to remove certain linguistic aberrations which affect us deeper than we\'d like to realize, such as: race is a misnomer. (A new alien race. A new race of Humans. The Human race). Such as: black. I once asked my father in 3rd grade, after coming home from school confused, why they called us black when we\'re brown. Once I attended Whittier College, they held an event which showed the documentation of how we are truly all various shades of brown, with the absence of melanin (albinos) because truly white. And, of course, I cannot discount the fact there may be people on the opposite end of the spectrum who are actually black; I just have never met one.\r\n\r\nNow, these things people always tell you, when mentioning, stop nitpicking, or, don\'t be so serious, or, gimmie a break. But these things were purposefully done to cause separation. I mean, does no one else find it odd that in a society began with the destruction of the Mexican and African livelihood, those two groups, somehow, have grown to dislike one another, with one group having a strong affinity towards Caucasian ethnicity?\r\n\r\nI find myself not experiencing the stereotypical African-American mindset, although I have lived in the heart of those who are. I find that most comedies, dramas, etc, reinforce those stereotypes. The only Tyler Perry film I have seem that attempts to move beyond that is \'The Family that Preys\'. Personally, I use the writing tools of knowing my heritage, and being at a position where I can see clearly certain things which I hope, when angled and redistributed to the people, will open their eyes.\r\n\r\nSo, yeah, I rap, but here is a sample of half a verse:\r\n\r\nsometimes feel like my mind lost it/\r\nsittin back countin drips out the faucet/\r\nused to kick up in Long Beach off 4th street all cautious/\r\nwith the monsters sniffin markers others claimin lawsuits\r\noff of small shit/ \r\nplus them good folks you\'d be hard pressed to find a city as diverse/ \r\ninstead of dealin dirt I\'d rather read Lorca \r\non the large scale of what\'s important \r\ndoubt you\'ll find a Porsche\r\nI\'ve seen the inside of a courtroom/ \r\nyeah but I grew from that\r\n\r\n\r\nCombined with hip hop, writing poetry, making films, one can hope to reach a wide range of people due to the separations in society -- where you have a small percentage of us in the \'high\' arts, with those same people who make up the majority reading that work, while \'us others\' are on the outside not reading the work and unable to receive whatever message there is for them to understand.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-US; rv:1.9.0.11) Gecko/2009060215 Firefox/3.0.11 (.NET CLR 3.5.30729)', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('112', '123', 'gaydegani', 'gaydegani@yahoo.com', 'http://wordsinplace.blogspot.com/', '99.186.193.174', '2009-07-06 12:41:29', '2009-07-06 16:41:29', 'They have a terrific botanical garden.  Definitely worth it to get mellow and refill the well.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 7.0; Windows NT 5.1; SU 3.23; GTB6; .NET CLR 2.0.50727)', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('113', '123', 'david', 'daveerlewine@yahoo.com', '', '68.33.40.219', '2009-07-06 17:36:26', '2009-07-06 21:36:26', 'CHECK OUT CALIFORNIA, MISSOURI - THAT\'S THE SHIT!!!!!!!  I spent a year there one weekend (okay many years over many weekends, staying with my then-gf\'s family).  For Christmas, I once was given a \"Jesus\" film by her family, which was extra sweet as I\'m Jewish.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 7.0; Windows NT 6.0; SLCC1; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; MDDC; .NET CLR 3.5.30729; .NET CLR 3.0.30618)', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
