('30335', '189', 'Jason', 'wingbiddlebaum@yahoo.com', '', '68.162.101.49', '2009-10-24 13:43:29', '2009-10-24 17:43:29', 'I just discovered your blog from a link on the Weave Magazine website. I\'ve read some of your work and like it, and obviously a lot of your posts here are the way all writers feel. My advice, passed on from a friend of mine, would be start at the top and work your way down with every piece you have. I started trying to publish in 2008 even though I\'d been writing for years, and I started submitting to the smaller magazines. A friend of mine who has been published in great places like McSweeney\'s and Hayden\'s Ferry Review started reading my stuff and said, \"Why aren\'t you starting at the top and working your way down rather than vice-versa?\" Of course, with this theory, it takes much longer to find a home for your piece, the rejection percentage is much higher as you\'re in the more competetive markets, but the reward is that much greater if a piece gets picked up. I don\'t mean by this to demean smaller markets whose work a lot of the time is as good if not better than some of the work in larger markets, but as a writer, you want the most public venue to demonstrate your talents. And when all the good markets say no, there\'s always the smaller places. You just have to develop a thick skin and be patient.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; Intel Mac OS X 10.4; en-US; rv:1.9.1.3) Gecko/20090824 Firefox/3.5.3', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
