('30506', '355', 'MoGa', 'molly.gaudry@gmail.com', '', '71.185.139.217', '2009-11-24 22:28:56', '2009-11-25 02:28:56', 'http://www.grammarphobia.com/grammar.html\r\n\r\n\"It\'s no longer considered a crime to . . . end a sentence with a preposition.\" Hooray.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; Intel Mac OS X 10_5_6; en-us) AppleWebKit/525.27.1 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/3.2.1 Safari/525.27.1', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('30693', '362', 'Rose', 'roseh400@yahoo.ca', 'http://rosehunterblog.blogspot.com/', '189.182.120.82', '2009-12-10 09:05:27', '2009-12-10 13:05:27', 'I like that you write about rejections too. I don\'t, much, because I think it will make me feel more rejected. I think I\'m wrong though.\r\n\r\nI received that letter from Kenyon Review too. Kenyon is one of those journals I keep submitting to, even though I KNOW (much like my previous relationship) that it\'s never going to work out for us. I like going back and taking the abuse, which is a bit like your description of your job search in the post above, but not that bad. (The compulsive Kenyon Review submissions. The relationship was definitely that bad.)\r\n\r\nThanks for the posts. I enjoy reading your blog.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 6.0; Windows NT 5.1; SV1; GTB6.3; .NET CLR 1.1.4322)', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('30509', '355', 'robert', 'robert@robertswartwood.com', 'http://www.robertswartwood.com', '24.152.219.224', '2009-11-25 04:29:18', '2009-11-25 08:29:18', 'Quick Fiction once sent me a request to donate to their journal. The letter had these boxes where I could check how much I wanted to give. If I remember correctly, there was a box for $1,000. Who the hell is donating that much? And if people ARE donating that much, how come Quick Fiction still doesn\'t offer to pay the writers anything, not even a flat fee of five or ten bucks? Ridiculous.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-US; rv:1.9.1.5) Gecko/20091102 Firefox/3.5.5 (.NET CLR 3.5.30729)', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('30511', '355', 'Adam Pieroni', 'adampieroni@quickfiction.org', 'http://www.quickfiction.org/', '63.146.184.126', '2009-11-25 15:09:21', '2009-11-25 19:09:21', 'I find this claim curious:\r\n\r\n<blockquote>Quick Fiction also offers subscriptions in their rejection letter.</blockquote>\r\n\r\nas we most certainly do not. And if we ever have, it was years ago, because I don\'t remember it. And just by way of clarification, our donation solicitations are not associated with our editorial responses. Any unwanted solicitations can be easily avoided by removing yourself from our opt-in email list, though they are so few and far between, I\'m surprised there\'s even a complaint.\r\n\r\nAnd to suggest that Quick Fiction, a tiny independent publication, is sitting miserly on a trove of donated cash? Now that\'s ridiculous.\r\n\r\nAdam Pieroni\r\n(publisher of Quick Fiction)', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; Intel Mac OS X 10_5_8; en-us) AppleWebKit/531.21.8 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/4.0.4 Safari/531.21.10', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('30699', '362', 'Amber', 'anoellesparks@gmail.com', '', '208.118.163.98', '2009-12-10 18:43:04', '2009-12-10 22:43:04', 'Oh, Roxane. Your posts are so marvelous. Even if they are sad and hurt you, which is not good--the pain at least obviously helps you to emit such beautiful sentences and phrases and word pictures, if that\'s worth anything. (I got a rejection from Kenyon, too, btw.) I can\'t believe that shit about the rewrite, though...I had NO IDEA editors did that! Rejections generally don\'t bother me too much, but I think my face would start bleeding or something if that happened to me. How terribly inconsiderate.\r\n\r\nI\'m from Minnesota, so I understand about the snow. It\'s not just snow. It\'s SNOW. It\'s oppressive and dangerous and a blanket separating you from other people and everything civilized and its heavy and quiet and cold and later it\'s dirty and soul-smothering. OH GOD I KNOW. I have written three separate stories about oppressive and horrible winter-related stuff, two of them fairly post-apocalyptic. And none of them planned.\r\n\r\nI don\'t really like D.C., where I live now, and I miss Minnesota for many reasons--but the snow is not one of them. And I will never, never, never move back there again because of it.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-US; rv:1.9.1.5) Gecko/20091102 Firefox/3.5.5 (.NET CLR 3.5.30729)', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('30516', '355', 'Adam Pieroni', 'adampieroni@quickfiction.org', 'http://www.quickfiction.org/', '63.146.184.126', '2009-11-25 16:14:12', '2009-11-25 20:14:12', 'No worries, Roxane; just clarifying. And the stuff about the cash was in response to one of the comments.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; Intel Mac OS X 10_5_8; en-us) AppleWebKit/531.21.8 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/4.0.4 Safari/531.21.10', '', '30515', '0', 'N'),
('30515', '355', 'Roxane', 'roxane@roxanegay.com', 'http://www.roxanegay.com', '24.247.41.152', '2009-11-25 15:38:04', '2009-11-25 19:38:04', 'Hi Adam. If Iâ€™ve misremembered the rejection letter, I apologize. There was no malice in my statement. Iâ€™m a Quick Fiction subscriber and I love the magazine and I never said anything about sitting on a load of cash. Iâ€™m an editor at a tiny magazine too. I know the deal', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; Intel Mac OS X 10.5; en-US; rv:1.9.1.5) Gecko/20091102 Firefox/3.5.5', '', '30511', '1', 'N'),
('30518', '355', 'david erlewine', 'daveerlewine@yahoo.com', '', '173.3.114.104', '2009-11-25 18:23:21', '2009-11-25 22:23:21', 'After seeing John Freeman of Granta and now Adam Pieroni of Quick Fiction respond to blog comments, I am inspired about the reach of these blogs and reminded to take a deep breath before hitting submit comment/publish (and to think what my mom would think).  \r\n\r\nI   I have gotten a number of QF rejections and don\'t recall anything about any subscriptions or donations.  Of course, as happens when I get rejections from places I\'m dying to get into, I sort of black out while reading the rejection so there\'s that.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 6.0; Windows NT 5.1; SV1; GTB6; .NET CLR 1.1.4322; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; .NET CLR 3.0.4506.2152; .NET CLR 3.5.30729; MS-RTC LM 8)', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('30519', '346', 'david erlewine', 'daveerlewine@yahoo.com', '', '173.3.114.104', '2009-11-25 18:29:50', '2009-11-25 22:29:50', 'just claim you are giving up writing for good and then come back into the fold with a (vestigal?) tail b/w your legs.  works great.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 6.0; Windows NT 5.1; SV1; GTB6; .NET CLR 1.1.4322; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; .NET CLR 3.0.4506.2152; .NET CLR 3.5.30729; MS-RTC LM 8)', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('30520', '346', 'Roxane', 'roxane@roxanegay.com', 'http://www.roxanegay.com', '24.247.41.152', '2009-11-25 18:40:58', '2009-11-25 22:40:58', 'Hi David. I have never felt the need to give up writing or announce I\'m giving up writing because whenever I\'ve had those urges, I\'ve known it was temporary! Maybe I will try it, though, and see what happens.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; Intel Mac OS X 10.5; en-US; rv:1.9.1.5) Gecko/20091102 Firefox/3.5.5', '', '30519', '1', 'N'),
('30700', '371', 'Ben White', 'benjamin.white@post.harvard.edu', 'http://benwhite.com', '70.124.126.170', '2009-12-10 20:22:36', '2009-12-11 00:22:36', 'The subject of book blogs was discussed recently. I think you may have brought it up. Either way, I\'d say this rejection-fest + job hunt makes for the most sadly funny blog-to-book-worthy reading. You should submit \"I Have Become Accustomed to Rejection\" to a chapbook contest. If they don\'t bite, tell them \"No, I reject <em>you</em>.\" Then write about that, too.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-US; rv:1.9.1.5) Gecko/20091102 Firefox/3.5.5 (.NET CLR 3.5.30729)', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('30522', '355', 'robert', 'robert@robertswartwood.com', 'http://www.robertswartwood.com', '24.152.219.224', '2009-11-26 00:46:17', '2009-11-26 04:46:17', 'My comment wasn\'t to suggest that QF is \"sitting miserly on a trove of donated cash,\" but to say that if people are donating up to $1,000, why aren\'t the contributing writers being paid at least SOMETHING for their work? (There are, what, about 25 stories in the current issue? A flat fee of $5 per story would work out to a penny a word and overall cost $125 ...) Personally, I\'m more apt to spend a few bucks if the request is for a subscription rather than a donation. At least with a subscription I\'m getting something more out of the deal besides a nice warm fuzzy feeling inside ... but maybe that just makes me selfish.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-US; rv:1.9.1.5) Gecko/20091102 Firefox/3.5.5 (.NET CLR 3.5.30729)', '', '30516', '0', 'N'),
