('34957', '236', 'Savannah Schroll Guz', 'savannahguz@yahoo.com', 'http://www.savannahschrollguz.com', '71.61.41.245', '2010-05-20 10:49:28', '2010-05-20 14:49:28', 'I just read this now...wow...yes, kids can be horrible. Absolutely horrible. When I went to private school from 3rd -6th grade, I was nearly drowned in the pool by the other kids. They actually tried to kill me. I also remember they used to giggle and scream and run to one side of the room and touch metal whenever I came within close proximity of them because they said if they touched metal it would protect them from me. One girl, who had a retainer said I could never hurt her because she was always touching metal. The teachers never really intervened in other issues, except for what happened in the pool. I totally symapthize with you. My formative years were a kind of horror, too.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 8.0; Windows NT 6.1; WOW64; Trident/4.0; SLCC2; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; .NET CLR 3.5.30729; .NET CLR 3.0.30729; Media Center PC 6.0; MDDC; InfoPath.2)', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('35139', '688', 'Tres Crow', 'trescrow@gmail.com', 'http://www.dogeatcrow.blogspot.com', '12.159.49.23', '2010-06-04 11:26:44', '2010-06-04 15:26:44', 'On the kids/responsibility thing, I would have to say that as someone who fairly recently crossed the veil to the other side, that I didn\'t really understand what responsibility was until I had a child. Now, of course, everyone\'s lives are different and I can\'t even presume to know what someone else is going through, so the following paragraphs should not be taken as a shot across the bow of all the non-parent peeps who read this blog. I can only speak to my own experience, and that experience has been that the sheer humanity of my child presses in on my life in so many ways that the concept of responsibility doesn\'t even really accurately reflect the conflated level of difficulty in the everyday activities that used to be so easy about 13 months ago.\r\n\r\nBut I think that if it could be reduced to one thing it would be that when it was just me and my wife our decisions effected only us and there was usually a one to one correlation between our actions and the resulting reactions. Now, every decision has to be filtered through the complicated matrices of whether this decision will kill our child, maim our child, cause society to think we are bad parents but otherwise leave our child relatively unharmed, psychologically scar our child for life, make it so that society will think our child mentally deficient, snub out our chances of raising the next Justin Timberlake who will then lavish us with money and a life of leisure in approx. 25 years, or any number of other possibilities.\r\n\r\nIn short, parenthood has made everything more difficult, and at no point in the last 13 months have my old, non-parenthood responsibilities let up in the slightest, therefore I have all of the old, difficult things that used to be hard for me, but also this whole additional level of difficulty which not only is difficult in and of itself but also makes all the old things that much more difficult.\r\n\r\nWhich brings me to my overall point, which is that it is a very good thing that my child is so darn cute and looks a lot like a little version of me and gives me the most sincere hugs I\'ve ever received in my life and is generally the best thing that\'s ever happened to me. Otherwise none of the preceding couple of paragraphs\' stuff would really be worth it. As it stands they are, and he is.\r\n\r\nI\'m just saying.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 6.0; Windows NT 5.1; SV1; .NET CLR 1.1.4322; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; .NET CLR 3.0.04506.30; .NET CLR 3.0.04506.648)', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('34959', '658', 'Tres Crow', 'trescrow@gmail.com', 'http://www.dogeatcrow.blogspot.com', '12.159.49.23', '2010-05-20 11:37:51', '2010-05-20 15:37:51', 'Roxane,\r\nI think that stumbling on your blog has to have been one of the most fortuitous circumstances so far in my relatively short writing career. Through you and your blog, not only have I been introduced to YOUR wonderful words, but also xTx\'s and Ethel\'s and Alan Stewart Carl\'s and Mr. Erlewine\'s, and Charles Dodd White\'s, and a whole host of others too numerous to mention.\r\n\r\nEveryday I\'m amazed by the amount of literary talent burbling just under the surface out there, in the wide world, shining their little lights for anyone who\'s interested in feeling something substantial to see.\r\n\r\nAnyway, thanks for making me laugh, and feel better about getting rejected myself. Keep up the good work, and keep your light shining bright.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 6.0; Windows NT 5.1; SV1; .NET CLR 1.1.4322; .NET CLR 2.0.50727; .NET CLR 3.0.04506.30; .NET CLR 3.0.04506.648)', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
