('37342', '972', 'Robert Laughlin', 'pc-privconfounder@sbcglobal.net', '', '75.7.152.40', '2010-09-15 10:44:43', '2010-09-15 14:44:43', 'I say, authors and readers alike should boycott these greedy magazines that charge for submissions. Congratulations on selling to Monkeybicycle.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 8.0; Windows NT 5.1; Trident/4.0; yie8)', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('37351', '972', 'Stephen', 'stephendlew@gmail.com', 'http://www.robotmelon.com', '174.29.118.223', '2010-09-15 14:29:08', '2010-09-15 18:29:08', 'I agree.  Three dollars is quite a bit for a form letter.  Although it would almost be worth it if the journal offered comments on the rejected pieces, and paid the contributors a little bit.  I came across a journal the other day that sent the authors two dollars via paypal, which is small, but really nice.\r\n\r\nAnd you\'re right, the cover for Monkeybicycle looks great!  I\'m excited the read your story (and everyone else\'s).', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; Intel Mac OS X 10.5; en-US; rv:1.9.2.9) Gecko/20100824 Firefox/3.6.9', '', '0', '0', 'Y'),
('37349', '972', 'Jason', 'enricopallazo@yahoo.com', 'http://www.jasonmjones.net', '65.242.114.226', '2010-09-15 13:56:44', '2010-09-15 17:56:44', 'I saw that Colorado Review was charging but still accepting manuscripts by post, and I sent them something by post that cost $1.22. Since they reply by e-mail, even if you send via post, and there\'s no need for a SASE, I would say that makes a big difference ($1.78 to be exact). Then when I saw on duotrope that Colorado was knocking people off in 3-6 days with form rejections, I kind of thought that was a bit messed up. $3 dollars for a 3-6 day form makes me question if they\'re reading beyond the first sentence or paragraph. I know quick response times don\'t always mean this is true, but to maintain the illusion, especially with a place that gets as many submissions as Colorado Review probably does, I need at least 2-3 weeks to pass to feel like they gave me a fair shake.  \r\n\r\nI like that with New England Review they state clearly that you can still submit by post for whatever that costs, and that if you are a subscriber, they\'ve waived the online fee now that they\'ve gone electronic. But still, $3 dollars is steep, and I tend to find something morally questionable in the practice of charging writers to submit regardless of how editors justify it in terms of \"well, it would cost you this much to send it USPS.\"  \r\n\r\nIf a journal charges, I tend to think they really need to 1. offer a personal response with a handful of helpful comments, and 2. pay the writers that they do select when that time comes both in hard cash and contributor copies. If they\'re not doing that, really they\'re just taking advantage of people\'s dreams and aspirations. But that\'s just my 2 cents on the subject.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-US; rv:1.9.2.9) Gecko/20100824 Firefox/3.6.9', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
