('44508', '1314', 'Jen', 'jen.michalski@gmail.com', 'http://jenmichalski.com', '71.166.21.202', '2011-02-19 12:19:20', '2011-02-19 16:19:20', 'Hang in there! We should really feel sorry for our SOs and not ourselves! My girlfriend is the most patient person on the planet, having to deal with my incessant mood swings about rejections and whether I\'ve platueaed, a terrible writer, blah, blah, blah. I think to myself, \"would I want to trade places with P. and live with myself?\" at which point I contemplate buying her the most expensive Jane Seymour Open Heart necklace ever. And then I don\'t. I know; I\'m unworthy.\r\n\r\nBut rejections are good for me--they really make me take a fiftieth look at a piece and discover what I could not see before, why it wasn\'t working. Or, conversely, I feel the same way as you--\"this is the greatest piece I\'ve ever written and it\'s been rejected a million trillion times!\"  I know a guy who wrote a short story that took seven years to publish. It wound up being in the Southern Review, which is not too shabby. I know I would probably have given up on a story well before that. \r\n\r\nBut this is the path we have chosen as writers. Continual humiliation and self-doubt for a little glimmer of success. Because even if you publish with HarperP or Simon &amp; Schuster or RH or whoever, you will still be insecure about the next book. The next thing. Whether people who read your book really enjoyed it or whether they are lying. \r\n\r\nSo embrace your Black Swan. Love her. Use cocoa butter body lotion so your skin doesn\'t get all crazy chapped. xo Jen', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.0; en-US; rv:1.9.2.14) Gecko/20110207 Firefox/3.6.14 (.NET CLR 3.5.30729) SearchToolbar/1.2', '', '0', '0', 'Y'),
