('43722', '1218', 'Ben', 'benjamin.white@post.harvard.edu', 'http://benwhite.com', '129.111.56.132', '2011-01-23 21:30:43', '2011-01-24 01:30:43', 'Two cents: Mirena has the same side effects as any progestin-only birth control, like the mini-pill women use while nursing or the injection depo-provera. The estrogen that\'s added to your common birth control pills is used to control the breakthrough bleeding/spotting many women complain of; it serves no purpose in preventing pregnancy. If the hormones are an issue, and they certainly are for a minority of women, there is also a copper-based IUD that has no systemic side effects (does not prevent periods either though, for what it\'s worth). If one doesn\'t have pelvic inflammatory disease or a high likelihood of getting chlamydia or gonorrhea, then IUDs are very very safe. \r\n\r\nIf the idea of having it up there for years is off-putting but the idea of a set-it-and-forget it solution is nice, there is a product called Implanon which is basically injected underneath the skin near your elbow. Same hormones, different location. The majority of young ob-gyns I know use this for their birth control. It requires no user effort, and consequently has been significantly more effective than the pill in the real world.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-US; rv:1.9.2.3) Gecko/20100401 Firefox/3.6.3 (.NET CLR 3.5.30729)', '', '0', '0', 'Y'),
