('43129', '1176', 'Dawn.', 'dawngrrrl@gmail.com', 'http://nouvelliste.tumblr.com', '65.60.229.228', '2011-01-09 18:32:54', '2011-01-09 22:32:54', '<i>When you think about it, blogging is kind of ridiculous isn’t it? The world is full of lonely people pouring their hearts out one pixel at a time hoping someone reaches out with pixels of their own to remind them, “You are not alone.”</i>\r\n\r\nThis is the kind of thing I already knew but when I read it written so tenderly I\'m thrilled and devastated at the same time.\r\n\r\n<i>I want to keep track of everything I read this year so I can be one of the cool kids who shows off their fancy reading list... So often people talk about these “famous” “important” writers and I must confess, I haven’t heard of most of them and that makes me feel like I’m not well read and not cool or smart enough.  For example, I’ve never read Barthelme. I don’t know who that dude is save for what I’ve gathered from folks who name drop that guy.</i>\r\n\r\nAmen! This is exactly how I feel whenever I read one of those \"What I Read in 2010/Best of 2010\" lists. I\'ve never read Barthelme either, besides name-dropping and quotes online. Usually I feel \"not well read and not cool or smart enough,\" but then I think of how many books I\'ve fiercely loved recently and I don\'t feel so bad. I don\'t want to read a book just because it\'s fashionably obscure. I want to read a book that calls out to me (if that makes any sense).\r\n\r\nThis is the first year I\'ve decided to keep track of all the books I read since I was 15. I used to do it all the time in my diaries for myself. I\'m also doing it for myself now--only difference is the list is in a Word document instead of a notebook.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.1; en-US; rv:1.9.2.13) Gecko/20101203 Firefox/3.6.13', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
