('46976', '1662', 'KRomeo', 'kromeo004@yahoo.com', 'http://magicanddreamsandgoodmadness.wordpress.com/about/', '68.194.46.215', '2011-07-03 12:41:24', '2011-07-03 16:41:24', 'This review is clever and sarcastic and had me cracking up. One of my favourite parts speaks eloquently of your revulsion for Labeouf: \"If I had to choose between death and being intimate with Shia using someone else’s vagina, I’d choose to die.\" Love it. I don\'t much care for him myself. Claiming he got to tap Fox was a totally shite move on his part. He\'d be so lucky. And I totally agree with you: Stratham is truly delicious. He can get it a la carte from me too.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1; WOW64; rv:5.0) Gecko/20100101 Firefox/5.0', '', '0', '0', 'Y'),
('46756', '1518', 'Laura', 'laurawithoutlabels@gmail.com', 'http://dearouterspace.blogspot.com/', '24.3.49.208', '2011-05-30 12:11:49', '2011-05-30 16:11:49', 'I think sometimes people need to be sad or bummed out. Writers or not, it\'s ok to be disappointed. I know some writers aren\'t bothered by rejection, and I\'m not bothered as much as I was when I first started, but sometimes when you just really love a journal and you know that your story would fit in their pages, well  - it can really suck to get a \"no thanks\" in response. \r\n\r\nI guess I question why it\'s bad to honor sadness and disappointment. Perhaps those feelings can push you toward a new realization or connection or character or image. And then you\'ll have a brilliant new story. There has to be a place between wallowing in sadness and total dismissal (not that you are doing that). At least, that\'s just my little insight for Monday.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_6_7) AppleWebKit/534.24 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/11.0.696.71 Safari/534.24', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
