('46993', '1673', 'Ashley Ford', 'acford01@gmail.com', 'http://thechicklitz.com', '68.51.91.57', '2011-07-04 15:06:06', '2011-07-04 19:06:06', 'I feel like I live in this post.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1; WOW64) AppleWebKit/534.30 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/12.0.742.112 Safari/534.30', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('46995', '1673', 'KRomeo', 'kromeo004@yahoo.com', 'http://magicanddreamsandgoodmadness.wordpress.com/about/', '68.194.46.215', '2011-07-04 18:44:40', '2011-07-04 22:44:40', 'Your post, as always, is thought provoking and has me thinking of just so many things. I agree with Ashley, I feel like I live in this post too cause it’s hitting so many cords in me. Reading your post I’m reminded of a story my best friend told me. She hails from Trinidad (as do I) and in high school, her classmates, who realized that she was ahead of them academically, would gather around her desk and force her to do their assignments. They would distort the ideals of affirmative action and say that they deserved an A or at least a passing grade merely because their ancestors were slaves. \r\n        One day her math teacher, tired of the bullying, put her to sit right next to him at the front of the class. Later that week those same students shot the teacher. My friend always assumed that he was shot because he intervened on her behalf. Thankfully, he wasn’t fatally wounded and recovered fully.  \r\n          Until I read your post it never really occurred to me that some of their behaviour could be chalked up to bluster. Perhaps they simply did not know how to read either and that was how their frustration and resentment presented itself. It’s hard to read about some of your past students’ backgrounds and not feel frustrated myself. It’s bad enough that some of them couldn’t read, but they also have to maintain an appearance of not wanting to do so. It’s just unreal and maddening. I’m also struck by how your nurturing infected your students with your sense of agency. The expression of their appreciation of that sounds like it was very moving.\r\n         I’m also reminded of two Latina college roommates who often said to me “you don’t act black,” meaning (well, what I thought it meant anyway) “you don’t walk and talk like so many of the blacks I see on TV.” What I was too young to have thought about saying to them and often wish that I had, is that I don’t know how to be black (or white or Latina) I only know how to be me. \r\n       Also, not only am I guilty of doing my fair share of online dating, I’ve visited niche  interral dating websites and two of my most significant relationships were with men that I met from dating websites. I love meeting people that can expose me to ideas and mentalities that are different from my own and don’t like dating anyone that’s too much like me either. I\'m not suggesting that this can\'t be achieved by not using online dating or non interracial dating but at times, I\'ve just found it easier to date who I want with online dating. Having said that, I haven’t done online dating, or any dating for that matter, in quite some time now. \r\nAnd on that note, I’ll go ahead and end this long ass, chatty response:)', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 5.1; en-US; rv:1.9.2.17) Gecko/20110420 Firefox/3.6.17', '', '0', '0', 'Y'),
