('47349', '1745', 'Rich Baiocco', 'r_baiocco@hotmail.com', 'http://shwardo.tumblr.com', '68.173.111.233', '2011-08-16 18:16:51', '2011-08-16 22:16:51', 'Hey Roxane\r\n\r\nI really like your short stories and they led me to your blog (which I also like--especially the rejection/acceptance part).  I don\'t know if you answer questions in the comments section, but I was curious as to what happens when you get solicited by a journal.  Do they come to you and ask if you have anything that would fit their style?  Or do they say they like your writing and would you write something new for them?  Do they give you an upfront warning that your piece may not be accepted or is it just common knowledge that nothing is guaranteed until the issue\'s Table Of Contents are laid out?\r\n\r\nIn any case, \"frustrating\" is a nice way to put it regarding solicitation rejections.  I can think of a few less tactful words, I\'m sure  \r\n\r\nHope to read more of your stuff.  \'The Shape Of My Mouth\' was one of the most giving things I\'ve ever read.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; U; PPC Mac OS X 10_4_11; en) AppleWebKit/533.19.4 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/4.1.3 Safari/533.19.4', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('47350', '1745', 'Roxane', 'roxane@roxanegay.com', 'http://www.roxanegay.com', '139.67.132.90', '2011-08-16 18:22:09', '2011-08-16 22:22:09', 'Hi Rich. Thanks for your comment. I do answer questions. When you\'re solicited it can work a couple different ways. Generally, an editor emails you and asks if you have something that might fit with their forthcoming issue(s). Sometimes, I\'ll send work I have on hand, and other times I\'ll write something new. Lately, I\'m starting to have to say no because I don\'t have a lot of new work that will fit certain magazines. There is rarely a guarantee of acceptance with a solicitation but, I\'d say 7 or 8 times out of 10, they\'ll take what you send. Solicitations are ALWAYS flattering and very appreciated but sometimes editors are extra awesome and they will tell you which stories of yours they enjoyed so you have some context for what they might be looking for from you. With new magazines, it is pretty difficult to know what they want since they don\'t have anything for you to read that will give you a sense of their aesthetic. Once something has been accepted, you have a guarantee your work will be published 99% of the time. It is very, very rare for a publication (at least in the literary world) to renege on an acceptance. Does this answer your question? Thanks for your kind words about Shape of My Mouth. That story means a lot to me so your comments mean a lot to me!', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_6_6) AppleWebKit/535.1 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/13.0.782.112 Safari/535.1', '', '47349', '0', 'N'),
