('47732', '949', 'BMX Spiele', 'Kruskie@hotmail.com', 'http://bmx.spiel-jetzt.org', '199.48.147.45', '2011-09-09 08:39:58', '2011-09-09 12:39:58', 'Unquestionably believe that which you stated. Your favorite reason appeared to be on the web the simplest thing to be aware of. I say to you, I definitely get irked while people think about worries that they plainly don\'t know about. You managed to hit the nail upon the top and defined out the whole thing without having side-effects , people could take a signal. Will likely be back to get more. Thanks', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 8.0; Windows NT 6.1; WOW64; Trident/4.0; SLCC2; Media Center PC 6.0; InfoPath.2; MS-RTC LM 8)', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('47467', '1773', 'Jason', 'enricopallazo@yahoo.com', 'http://www.jasonmjones.net', '65.242.114.226', '2011-08-24 12:18:18', '2011-08-24 16:18:18', 'One problem I\'ve always had in arguing, similar to you wishing you had a five second delay, comes from the fact that as I kid, I was picked on pretty mercilessly in elementary school. As a defense mechanism, I developed this ability to go for the throat. A kid on the playground would say, \"Ew, Jason\'s gross cause he picks his nose,\" and I\'d reply, \"Your mamma\'s doing the mailman and that\'s why she and your daddy are getting divorced.\" The result was that I learned how to develop a thick skin while at the same time sending the other kid away in tears. This worked on the playground. In adult discourse, it doesn\'t work so well, but I\'d done it for so long that my mind still goes there whenever I feel threatened. I hate it that it does that, but it does, so I\'ve had to learn ultimately to just keep my mouth shut and walk away. This also isn\'t the best way to engage in disagreement in the adult world, but it\'s probably better than pointing out to my boss that\'s she just taking her shit out on me because she\'s frustrated because her husband\'s in the closet and she isn\'t getting any.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.1; en-US; rv:1.9.2.3) Gecko/20100401 Firefox/3.6.3', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('47468', '1773', 'Roxane', 'roxane@roxanegay.com', 'http://www.roxanegay.com', '139.67.132.90', '2011-08-24 12:22:02', '2011-08-24 16:22:02', 'It\'s funny you should say that, Jason. I was tormented through most of grade school, middle school, and half of high school. It eventually made me vicious because being picked on so much made me absolutely feral when I realized I had a mouth on me. I have to believe a lot of how people respond to disagreement comes from once being the odd one out.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_6_8) AppleWebKit/535.1 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/13.0.782.215 Safari/535.1', '', '47467', '0', 'N'),
('47479', '1773', 'Michael Fischer', 'cmfischer_78@netzero.com', '', '99.91.75.161', '2011-08-25 10:46:10', '2011-08-25 14:46:10', 'One general issue I have with critiques/discussions of race &amp; representation in the arts is that almost all of them focus on bestsellers, Hollywood blockbusters, or TV shows.  By no means am I a cultural snob, but I\'m pretty sure I, as a white writer, could write a literary novel written from the POV of a black man or woman, and hardly anyone would even discuss it. Barry Hannah had some interesting depictions of black characters (some might say racist) to say the least and only a few people ever wrote about it (the only one who comes to mind is Major Jackson, and his points on Hannah were part of a larger discussion). I like your essay a lot, but I\'m concerned that people will assume the intentional lack of nuance in Hollywood always applies everywhere, so that a writer who is not writing to sell movie tickets and buckets of popcorn will be shouted down or suspiciously lumped with millionaire producers or directors of movies like \"The Help\" because he or she dared to write black characters. It\'s just really strange to me how \"The Help\" (and other similar works) have come to stand for a supposed larger trend across the board, since what I\'ve noticed is that most white literary writers aren\'t even writing characters who aren\'t white. The same can be said for social class, too--most literary writers only write stories within their own social classes. To me, this is almost just as bad.', '0', '1', 'Opera/9.80 (Windows NT 6.1; U; Edition United States Local; en) Presto/2.9.168 Version/11.50', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('47484', '1770', 'Jason Jordan', 'circus_brimstone@yahoo.com', 'http://poweringthedevilscircus.blogspot.com', '70.60.17.66', '2011-08-25 15:54:20', '2011-08-25 19:54:20', '\"Diet Cherry Pepsi–the only soda/pop that matters.\"\r\n\r\nYou\'re dead to me.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.0) AppleWebKit/535.1 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/13.0.782.215 Safari/535.1', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('47492', '1773', 'Fred', 'Freed@gmail.com', '', '98.212.203.140', '2011-08-26 08:45:46', '2011-08-26 12:45:46', 'I don\'t think anyone\'s claiming that most white writers do it, like it\'s a trend or something. What\'s being widely asked is that if they do it, they do it well, because in most cases when they do it, they do it badly.\r\n\r\nIt sounds like you\'re in effect worried about white writers being stereotyped. If so, that\'s silly. If you\'re going to take a minute or so to think about race, shouldn\'t you be more concerned about stereotypes imposed on non-white writers, and characters?', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (iPod; U; CPU iPhone OS 4_2_1 like Mac OS X; en-us) AppleWebKit/533.17.9 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/5.0.2 Mobile/8C148 Safari/6533.18.5', '', '47479', '0', 'N'),
('47493', '1773', 'Michael Fischer', 'cmfischer_78@netzero.com', '', '99.74.224.177', '2011-08-26 09:26:05', '2011-08-26 13:26:05', 'Fred,\r\n\r\nI\'m sorta confused by your reply, because it doesn\'t seem engaged with what I actually wrote. One, I never said or implied anyone is \"claiming\" anything.  Two, I said I liked Roxane\'s essay a lot, and though I didn\'t list specific reasons why, it\'s safe to assume that I liked it for the same obvious reasons most others liked it--that is, her points on writing about \"difference\" and how often it\'s \"done wrong\" or poorly. My point was that it\'s important we don\'t stop at analyzing Hollywood movies and potboiler novels. \r\n\r\nI\'m also not worried about white writers \"being stereotyped\" and agree with you that all writers should have enough common sense to think complexly about race or any sort of difference.  Really, to quote Roxane, a lot of this comes down to \"common sense\"; one doesn\'t have to be a scholar of race to imbue his or her characters with interesting complexity.  A cliche or stereotype is a cliche or stereotype 99% of the time because the writing isn\'t interesting or complex.', '0', '1', 'Opera/9.80 (Windows NT 6.1; U; Edition United States Local; en) Presto/2.9.168 Version/11.50', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
