('47555', '1781', 'Jason', 'enricopallazo@yahoo.com', 'http://www.jasonmjones.net', '65.242.114.226', '2011-08-30 15:18:28', '2011-08-30 19:18:28', 'I got a personal rejection from West Branch last week too where the EIC listed the details he liked in my story and then said why they ultimately rejected it, and I looked at duotrope and did the math....out of something like 850 rejections 3% are personal which means only 25 of those people got personal rejections. I too took it as something of an acceptance. It\'s actually been a while since I received a rejection I felt so good about, even when I\'ve gotten personal ones. Kind of funny how that works, isn\'t it?', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.1; en-US; rv:1.9.2.3) Gecko/20100401 Firefox/3.6.3', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('47559', '1781', 'Laura', 'lauraelizabethdavis@gmail.com', '', '208.127.247.163', '2011-08-30 19:53:32', '2011-08-30 23:53:32', 'I\'m so glad you wrote about the VMAs. I was writing a big ole blog post about Beyonce being pregnant and then I felt sheepish for a moment because writers aren\'t supposed to watch TV much less silly MTV award shows and then blog about them. \r\n\r\nThen I read this and remembered that Ira Glass watched the OC so all those people who only watch NOVA or use their TVs to grow organic herbs can shove it. I love me some pop culture for moments like Beyonce\'s performance. She was seriously magical and that song was awesomely happy and it was super awesome and adorable to see her all bursting with happy-happy-joy-joy. \r\n\r\nOk, I\'ve got to go write a sestina now or something.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_6_8) AppleWebKit/535.1 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/13.0.782.215 Safari/535.1', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
('47575', '1745', 'plangu', 'planguh@hotmail.co.uk', '', '94.8.188.111', '2011-08-31 18:00:36', '2011-08-31 22:00:36', '\'I mean, I’m guessing that is where he works because IT IS NEVER EXPLAINED\'\r\n\r\nIt is shown.  It shouldn\'t need to be explained.\r\n\r\n\'Freida Pinto, is… a vet maybe. IT IS NEVER EXPLAINED.\'\r\n\r\nJames Franco is walking through a zoo...then he\'s in her office.  I don\'t think the audience needs to be told that she is a vet.  Seems kinda obvious.\r\n\r\n\'We know they have jobs but we never, ever see them at this jobs\'\r\n\r\nWe also never see them going to the toilet, or brushing their teeth.  \r\n\r\n\'Other things that fell into that fiery red plot hole...basically, everything ever\'\r\n\r\nNone of the things mentioned in that paragraph are part of the overall narrative, or relevant.\r\n\r\n\'and then he is taken to the San Bruno Primate Sanctuary. We’re not super clear on why\'\r\n\r\nAren\'t we?  He has attacked a human...this is what happens.  And as the lady said, they are lucky that he was not put down.  \r\n\r\nCan I ask, in all sincerity, is this the first movie you have ever seen? Honestly seems like it might be a parody of a review.  I get that you don\'t like Franco, that\'s cool, albeit subjective.  But the \'plot holes\' you flag up simply aren\'t plot holes.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_6_8) AppleWebKit/534.50 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/5.1 Safari/534.50', '', '0', '0', 'Y'),
('47576', '1745', 'Roxane', 'roxane@roxanegay.com', 'http://www.roxanegay.com', '66.116.26.170', '2011-08-31 18:06:29', '2011-08-31 22:06:29', 'I beg to differ, re: the plot holes and I see movies almost daily--there\'s nothing sincere about your question so why pretend? This is my blog. I pointed out plot holes that bothered me. They didn\'t bother you. That\'s fine. This too is subjective.  Freida Pinto is shown working at a zoo, tsking over Caesar. That is the whole of what we learn about her. Look, I don\'t need to know every damn thing about what she does in her work day and yes, I have a fucking brain so I can put it together but let\'s not act like the plot of this movie was well developed. We\'re not really shown where Franco works. We see the building and we see labs and people doing things.  We don\'t know if he\'s a geneticist or what. We don\'t know much about him at all. We\'re not clear on why, for example, Caesar wasn\'t taken to a zoo, or research facility or any number of places where exotic animals are sent when captured.  I think it\'s a sad statement on movies today that you\'re satisfied with these plot details that are so flimsy. Finally, a lot of this is tongue in cheek. That\'s pretty obvious.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_6_8) AppleWebKit/535.1 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/13.0.782.112 Safari/535.1', '', '47575', '0', 'N'),
