('47830', '1804', 'ann ryles', 'annrylesca@gmail.com', '', '70.137.153.116', '2011-09-12 08:49:08', '2011-09-12 12:49:08', 'I never doubted the realness of the characters in Disgrace, whatever their race.  That was one of the reasons I loved the novel so much, because of how real the characters were to me.  But when I came across Gordimer\'s reaction, I questioned my judgment.  As a white female from the U.S., I knew I didn\'t have the context to assess the novel as Gordimer had.  Ultimately, the novel became even more morally complex for me, which I think is one of its tremendous strengths. \r\n \r\nHere\'s another reaction, from the same NYT essay in which Gordimer was quoted, which is more in line with how I feel about the novel ultimately:\r\n\r\nHomi Bhabha, a Harvard English professor and the de facto dean of postcolonial theory (and a friend of Coetzee’s), says the novelist’s power lies precisely in his ability to unsettle. “Disgrace,” he said in a recent interview, is a work of “open seams” rather than “suturing.” In a moment of “real social, historical, psychic crisis,” he said, Coetzee makes readers feel their anxiety rather than resolving it “in the way in which we as progressive liberals would want him to do.” For Bhabha, “Disgrace” is so powerful because it “allows people to project onto it some of their own most heartfelt but violent feelings.”\r\n\r\nI hope you\'ll comment more on your blog about Coetzee\'s other books, Roxane.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_6_8) AppleWebKit/534.50 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/5.1 Safari/534.50', '', '0', '0', 'Y'),
('47834', '1804', 'Terri', 'tfredrick@gmail.com', '', '139.67.133.26', '2011-09-12 12:17:09', '2011-09-12 16:17:09', 'Thanks, Roxane. I really appreciate you watching this movie for me that I would never have been able to sit through. How long until the Straw Dogs summary? The preview alone almost had me running from the theater. \r\n\r\nWhen it comes to fictional movies, I am not strong.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_6_8) AppleWebKit/534.50 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/5.1 Safari/534.50', '', '0', '0', 'Y'),
('47837', '1804', 'Dawn.', 'dawngrrrl@gmail.com', 'http://nouvelliste.tumblr.com', '75.180.24.47', '2011-09-12 14:29:11', '2011-09-12 18:29:11', 'I felt a similar way about Michael Kimball\'s <i>Us</i>. I thought it was interesting and occasionally touching, but overall I didn\'t feel much of a connection to the characters because everything fell somewhat flat. I went back and forth between liking and disliking the book so many times while reading it. It was a mixed experience but I still want to read <i>Dear Everybody</i>. I have a big hard on for epistolary fiction, as you know.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.1; en-US; rv:1.9.2.22) Gecko/20110902 Firefox/3.6.22', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
