('47997', '1896', 'ann ryles', 'annrylesca@gmail.com', '', '70.137.144.185', '2011-10-10 13:21:07', '2011-10-10 17:21:07', 'I haven\'t seen this ad.  But in a strange coincidence I was reading \"A Small, Good Thing\" by Raymond Carver right after I\'d read your blog entry wondering about these names.  In the story, an eight-year-old boy is injured in a car accident.  His mother is a white woman (I\'m assuming her race, correctly, I\'m sure) named Ann.  Ann encounters a \"Negro\" family in a waiting room at the hospital.  The family includes a woman named Evelyn, whose son (I presume, the story doesn\'t specify the relation) Franklin has been cut with a knife at a party.  Ann thinks \"[s]he wanted to talk more with these people who were in the same kind of waiting she was in.  She was afraid, and they were afraid.  They had that in common.\"   Both Ann\'s son and Franklin die.\r\n\r\nTotally random?  Probably.  But still odd, for me, to have read your question and then stumble across the names in the story attached to these characters.', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Macintosh; Intel Mac OS X 10_6_8) AppleWebKit/534.50 (KHTML, like Gecko) Version/5.1 Safari/534.50', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
