('48090', '1979', 'Jason', 'enricopallazo@yahoo.com', 'http://www.jasonmjones.net', '65.242.114.226', '2011-11-04 13:45:33', '2011-11-04 17:45:33', 'I actually like Visit from the Goon Squad a lot. My problem with Egan being in there is that she won the Pulitzer Prize for the work this story is a part of. I know it\'s call Best American Short Stories and winning the Pulitzer would certainly qualify her as best, but when I come to an anthology part of me really wants to see newer younger talent. There was a point there when Alice Munro had a story every year in BASS for like 12 years in a row. Seriously, I already know who  Alice Munro is, I like her, and if I want to read her, I\'ll check a collection out of the library. I don\'t really need BASS to introduce her to me every year. \r\n\r\nFor a long time, this is why I liked the non-required anthology better. There was work in there from many disparate sources including places like Hobart and Monkeybicycle. But now they\'ve gone the way of New Yorker/Harper\'s/Atlantic too. I wonder, is it pressure from the publisher? Put bigger names in the anthology, magazines with greater reputations so they sell more?', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows; U; Windows NT 6.1; en-US; rv:1.9.2.3) Gecko/20100401 Firefox/3.6.3', '', '48082', '0', 'N'),
