('48211', '2067', 'Babe Runner', 'letitiamoffitt@yahoo.com', 'http://baberunner.blogspot.com/', '50.129.98.47', '2011-11-29 12:52:09', '2011-11-29 16:52:09', 'There\'s a scene in Annie Hall where the Diane Keaton character tells Woody Allen that her \"Grammy Hall\" hates Jews. Woody\'s left staring at her like, uh, OK, I\'m supposed to say what now?  You\'re absolutely right about the way people weirdly seem to need to absolve themselves by mentioning their racist relatives. As for your comments on racism in liberal academia, I agree -- if anything sometimes it seems even worse among this segment because there\'s the assumption that academics are morally superior. I\'m reading Malcolm Gladwell\'s \"Blink,\" which has an interesting (if too brief) section about unconscious racist assumptions. What people believe in their conscious minds (\"I love people of all races! We are all equal! Yay rainbow!\") is, big shock, not often consistent with their unconscious assumptions, which are influenced heavily by an environment that, for example as illustrated in the book, associates \"black\" with \"bad\" and \"white\" with \"good.\" Nobody wants to admit they have these associations, but almost everyone does (even, he admits, Gladwell himself). And denying you have those associations (a la \"liberal academia\") only makes things worse because then you have no way of recognizing and changing racist behavior. [Gladwell does note one easy way to change these assumptions ... more on this at RM later on.]', '0', '1', 'Mozilla/4.0 (compatible; MSIE 7.0; Windows NT 5.1)', '', '0', '0', 'N'),
